example.p:
Consider the extremely trivial system of equations in one variable, A\vect{x}=\vect{b} with
            A&=\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\end{bmatrix}
            &
            \vect{x}&=\colvector{x_1}
            &
            \vect{b}&=\colvector{5\\15}
              Quite clearly this system has no solution.  Forming the normal equations we get the silly system \begin{bmatrix}5\end{bmatrix}\colvector{x_1}=\colvector{35} which has the unique solution x_1=7.  What is more interesting is that A\colvector{7} = \colvector{7\\14}.  This is a vector in \csp{A} and the difference \vect{r}=\colvector{5\\15}-\colvector{7\\14}=\colvector{-2\\1} is orthogonal to the columns of A, in other words \vect{r} is in the orthogonal complement of the column space of A.  Geometrically, the point (5,15) is not on the line y=2x, but (7,14) is.  The line has slope 2, while the line segment joining (5,15) to (7,14) has slope -\frac{1}{2}, making it perpendicular to the line.  So (7,14) is the point on the line closest to (5,15) and leads to the solution x_1=7 of the resulting system.

Consider the simple system of equations in two variables, A\vect{x}=\vect{b} with
            A&=\begin{bmatrix}1&-1\\2&3\\3&0\end{bmatrix}
            &
            \vect{x}&=\colvector{x_1\\x_2}
            &
            \vect{b}&=\colvector{1\\5\\-2}
              If you try to solve this system, say by row-reducing an augmented matrix, you will discover that there is no solution.  The vector \vect{b} is not in the column space of A. The normal equations give the system \begin{bmatrix}14&5\\5&10\end{bmatrix}\colvector{x_1\\x_2}=\colvector{5\\14} which has the unique solution x_1=-\frac{4}{23}, x_2=\frac{171}{115}.  What is more interesting is that A\colvector{-\frac{4}{23}\\\frac{171}{115}} = \colvector{-\frac{191}{115}\\\frac{473}{115}\\-\frac{12}{23}}.  This is a vector in \csp{A} and the difference \vect{r}= \colvector{1\\5\\-2}- \colvector{-\frac{191}{115}\\\frac{473}{115}\\-\frac{12}{23}}= \colvector{\frac{306}{115}\\\frac{102}{115}\\-\frac{34}{23}} is orthogonal to both of the columns of A, in other words \vect{r} is in the orthogonal complement of the column space of A.  Geometrically, the point (1,5,-2) is not on the plane spanned by the columns of A, which has equation 9x+3y-5z=0, but (-\frac{191}{115},\,\frac{473}{115},\,-\frac{12}{23}) is on the plane.  The plane has a normal vector 9\vec{i}+3\vec{j}-5\vec{k}, while the vector joining (1,5,-2) to (-\frac{191}{115},\,\frac{473}{115},\,-\frac{12}{23}) is \frac{306}{115}\vec{i}+\frac{102}{115}\vec{j}-\frac{34}{23}\vec{k}, which is a scalar multiple of the normal vector to the plane.  So (-\frac{191}{115},\,\frac{473}{115},\,-\frac{12}{23}) is the point on the plane closest to (1,5,-2) and leads to the solution x_1=-\frac{4}{23}, x_2=\frac{171}{115} of the resulting system.

subsection.p:
What does a solution to the normal equations look like for our economic forecasting model?  As discussed above A is a 720\times 2 matrix, where the first column has the numbers of construction permits, c_i for 1\leq i\leq 720, and the second column is all ones.  The vector \vect{b} contains the 720 values of the interest rate, r_i, 1\leq i\leq 720.  So 
        \adjoint{A}A&=\begin{bmatrix}\sum c_i^2&\sum c_i\\\sum c_i&720\end{bmatrix}
        \adjoint{A}\vect{b}&=\begin{bmatrix}\sum c_ir_i\\\sum r_i\end{bmatrix}   Then, 
        \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix}
        &=\vect{x}=\inverse{\left(\adjoint{A}A\right)}\adjoint{A}\vect{b}
        &=\inverse{\begin{bmatrix}\sum c_i^2&\sum c_i\\\sum c_i&720\end{bmatrix}}
        \begin{bmatrix}\sum c_ir_i\\\sum r_i\end{bmatrix}
        &=\frac{1}{720\sum c_i^2 - \left(\sum c_i\right)^2}
        \begin{bmatrix}720&-\sum c_i\\-\sum c_i&\sum c_i^2\end{bmatrix}
        \begin{bmatrix}\sum c_ir_i\\\sum r_i\end{bmatrix}
        &=\frac{1}{720\sum c_i^2 - \left(\sum c_i\right)^2}
        \begin{bmatrix}720\sum c_ir_i-\sum c_i\sum r_i\\-\sum c_i\sum c_ir_i + \sum c_i^2\sum r_i\end{bmatrix}
        The expressions above can be cleaned up some, but the point is to see that we have an expression for each of a and b, that depends soley on the 720 pairs of data points (c_i, r_i), 1\leq i\leq 720.  These expressions may look familiar as the most basic case of linear regression.  Exercise asks you to derive these expressions, and in the more typical order.  With estimates in hand, you can now consult the number of construction permits issued and form a prediction of interest rates.

But it gets better.  Consider solving the system A\vect{x}=\vect{b}.  Suppose A has rank n and we have a thin QR decomposition of A, A=QR where Q has orthogonal columns and R is upper triangular with positive diagonal entries.  Notice in particular that R is invertible.  Then
        \adjoint{Q}\vect{b}
              &=\inverse{\left(\adjoint{R}\right)}\adjoint{R}\adjoint{Q}\vect{b}=\inverse{\left(\adjoint{R}\right)}\adjoint{A}\vect{b}
        &=\inverse{\left(\adjoint{R}\right)}\adjoint{A}A\vect{x}=\inverse{\left(\adjoint{R}\right)}\adjoint{R}\adjoint{Q}A\vect{x}
        &=\adjoint{Q}QR\vect{x}=R\vect{x}
          This system has an upper triangular coefficient matrix, so one round of back-solving will provide a solution for \vect{x}.  And the product \adjoint{Q}\vect{b} will be reasonably well-behaved due to the orthogonal columns of Q.  Notice that in the case of a square matrix A, the matrix Q will be invertible, and the same system that in general leads to the least-squares solution will also provide the exact solution in this special case.

statement.p:
Compute the least-squares solution to the system \(A\vect{x}=\vect{b}\).  Compute the residual vector associated with your solution. 
                    A&=\begin{bmatrix}1&1\\0&0\\2&3\end{bmatrix}
                    &
                    \vect{b}&=\colvector{2\\1\\4}

solution.p:
We compute the pieces of the normal equations
                    \adjoint{A}A&=\begin{bmatrix}5 & 7\\7 & 10\end{bmatrix}
                    &
                    \adjoint{A}\vect{b}&=\colvector{10\\14}
                  So the solution is \vect{x}=\inverse{\begin{bmatrix}5 & 7\\7 & 10\end{bmatrix}}\colvector{10\\14}=\begin{bmatrix}10 & -7\\-7 & 5\end{bmatrix}\colvector{10\\14}=\colvector{2\\0}  The residual is the difference A\vect{x}-\vect{b} = \begin{bmatrix}1&1\\0&0\\2&3\end{bmatrix}\colvector{2\\0}-\colvector{2\\1\\4}=\colvector{0\\-1\\0}  Notice that residual is indeed orthogonal to the column space of A.
